review_blob: 1L plastic. Pours golden, flat. No head, carbonation or strong aroma. Mild lager smell. Feels like a flat pilsner with extra alcohol added. Does warm you up. Not revolting, but nothing good about it. It is heavily sweet and sharp with alcohol. Thin bodied - barely above watery. Not my kind of fortified lager.

33cl. Batch 2015. BBE 29.03.19 Warmth fills you from the first sip. Aroma of earthy peppers, honey, wooden casks, burnt sugar, massive malts and all is submerged in alcohol haze. Darker and clearer than 2015. Flat as the country it is made in - i.e. very gently, tiny carbonation bumps. Perfect for the style. Pleasantly sweet, yet dry. A bit mouth numbing, peppery, and very closely reminds me of good Scotch. Sugars are complex, and actually somewhat of a faro style like. Look for them - youll love it. No excessive hoppiness nor bitterness. No yeas leftovers, no unnatural esters, no wet cardboard - just pure malt extract and sweet sweet alcohol. Maturing will do some good to it. I am already hyped to get barrel aged version. In comparison to the last years one - this is more mature, more complex, more smooth and much more balanced. I liked the last year a bit more: it was raw pure energy, never done before in Estonia, it was more fun and it was 1/2 the price :-) This is like single malt whiskey - you pay more, and do not drink it but savour it. Thank You Phjala team for doing this. Sign me up for 2017.

50cl. Pours slightly hazy full golden, with nice thin head that stays. Citrusy and fruity aroma. Gently bitter, very smooth, medium to full bodied, pleasantly carbonated. Finish is long with some sweetness to it. As mentioned, had it first from Drink Baar. Food pairings are well described in J.Ramsden book. Bottle rated on 15.04.2016

33cl BBE 03.17. Pours pitch black with ashy grey head. Aroma of coffee, dark roasted malts, yeast and vinegar. Yeast and vinegar like acidity transfers to the taste. It might be a positive surprize to those who like acidobacillus beer, because it feels to me this is the one porter with it. Ashy and powdery, yet malty and espresso like. I like some parts of the taste idea, but I kind of hate second sour part of it. Pours thick, but feels thin. Slightly below medium mody. More carbonation than you average porter. Finish is sour and dry. First few sips were impressive, and I thought that we have a strong baltic porter example, but unfortunately sediment kicked in, and I became disappointed. Definitely there are fans of this kind of porter (those who enjoy Phjala dog beers (Kreuzberg etc)). I do not want EV to be sour (deep meaning about Estonia etc.). It is harsh sour and bitter reality, but make EV99 or EV100 sweeter.

50cl bottle. Pours dull straw goldenlike. Thin head, ok lacing. Taste is a bit metallic and sweet. Stale bread aftertaste. Everything that goes with the style of Svtl. Not my type of beer, but is overal a drinkable session lager.

50cl can. New design. This is the most interesting low alcohol beer that I have had recently. Smooth and gentle aroma of malt and faint hops. Medium body, smooth and velvety texture. Pleasant sweet aftertaste. I believe that previous ratings are for an old recipe/can. Best low alcohol available in Estonia at the moment. Beats Mikkeller Drinkin the Sun. Different style, but serves the same purpose.

33cl. Pours dark clear orange. Aroma of beer and crisps. Gently malty, a bit bitter, heavily carbonated, though pours without head. Below medium bodied, soft, easy. A bit dry closer to finish. Overall, a nice try on the topic of ales. Very drinkable and balanced beer.

33cl bottle. Metallic and malty - pleasant aroma of malt, minus all the nasty notes. Some coffee and dust in aroma. Extremely metallic and powdery taste. Also some licorice. Feels like sawdust infused with beer, even though it pours clear dark amber. No visible sediment, but it sticks to tongue as wet toilet paper. Above light, sticky, average carbonated brew. Ok to try, and a beautiful bottle (hombru much?).

50cl BBE 23/08/16 Pours pale straw/golden with thin head. Slightly below medium carbonation. Aroma of sweet sugars, and fain malts. Tastes also rather sweet. Gently fizzy, crispy and lightly bitter. Thin, simple, quicly and calmly disappearing finish. Below medium body, velvety and silky thin. Goes down quicker than water. A nice "session" lager - summer bbq and a six-pack or two of these.. aka "Estonian Summer Dream".
50cl bottle. A very nice example of non abv beer. Clean, malty, hoppy and refreshing. Absolutely nothing to write about. Decent 0% lager.
All medium: tap/can/bottle. Simple pale lager. Get a case and that is it. Tap is my fav. Burgers and Bud.

50cl can. Nice aroma of caramelized wheat. Soft and pleasant. A bit of toffee. Pours darker kind of hazy orange with thick head that stays. Zero lacing. Creamy, ashy, wheaty, weak and dusty. Some caramel again. A bit of coriander, yeast and dry powdered finish. Not bad, but not exactly enjoyable. Below medium texture. Again, dusty and rough, even though the head is nice and smooth. Overall, a simple caramel infused, carbonated wheat solution. A bit like porridge pot wash water (I said that before, and I say it again). I really liked its simple aroma, and toffee feeling to it, but texture and massive dusty, powdery dryness is not to my liking.
FTA: Somwhere around summer 2012. Two "beer-shakes" side by side. Simple shandy. Nothing more.

0.25cl. Gentle A.Le Coqis sour dough aroma, faint malt, and fain hops. Pours no idea how, but head inside the bottle was frothy and thick. Bottles is good for 1 and 1/2 sips - no point in pouring. Gently sour and sweet, hops are noted in bitterness. Somewhat wheat tones are present. Strong example of a medium bodied lager. Kind of creamy, pleasantly carbonated, well rounded. Clean, gently bitter, finish. I would love to see the same recipe in a bigger package. It is a nice lager, and it is good summer easygoing beer.
FTA: I am quite sure I have noted this one. This was a curious fruit beer variation. Probably single batch. Simple summer lager, with some fruit juice added.

FTA: This was a second comeback of the lite beer. It was more potent, and less cal. Still drinkable. I always considered them as nice BBQ beer - drink all evening, and not get drunk. 4.2% is similar to A.Le.Coq Pilsner, but this one was better.

50cl. Fresh beer as of March.2016. Clear golden, gently hoppy, medium bodied, and pleasantly carbonated. A bit sour in the end. Overal, a solid low alcohol product. Considering the price of ~.60EUR it is cheaper than bottled water. I like it.

33cl as a new Antvark Dark Lager. Pours clear transparent amber brown. Thick artificial head. Aroma of malts. No hops. First sip is really nice - fresh, thick, creamy, malty, caramelized and gently bitter.Very similar to a diluted Saku Tume. Minus points for strong metallic aftertaste in the aftertaste. Ok lager for what it is, but it has nothing to do with Dunkel/Tmavy.

50cl meant for Estonian market. No swingtop. Still fancy bottles is used. Cherry and decent lager mix. Aromatic, malty, medium bodied and overly sweet (bottle says it is sweet to the max). Surprised it is seated under lambic. I would say it is a lager mix. At least for a quick bottle taste.

33cl. As Saku Antvrk. Clean aroma of spring floral hops, fruity and nice. Pours clear orange with ok frothy head, and some lacing. Medium bitter, clear and gentle. A bit of sweetness in the background. Light to medium bodied, oily and slick, does not scratch your mouth with IBU, medium carbonation, nice fainting aftertaste. ABV is suitable. Overal, a very good result. I would serve it even below 8degC as suggested. Mine was at at 5 initialy, but warmer it gets - its drinkability diminishes exponentially.

50cl. This time Saku missed. It is not at all similar to Saku Le Mans, and not really similar to Valge/Stuttgart. Beautiful aroma and beautiful head. Full of hops and wheat, and you really prepare yourself for a positive surprise. But no, once you have a sip, you feel only some yeasty and sour slimy liquid. Full of powdery sediment and really unfiltered. But the grains are really coarse this time, and they scratch your throat. It is not dry, not sweet, it is just quite thin. Some carbonation, barely above flat. No finish whatsoever. Clean mouth after 20 seconds. And you forget about the taste in 30s. Overal - feels like some really thin and slimy wheat porridge carbonated water with hops. Sourness is nice, aroma is nice, even yeast is pleasant, but all together is just a chaotic mixture, out of proportion, not balanced... you get the point. A. Le Coq Weizen *(Volfas Engelman Balta Pinta) is much more well balanced.

33cl. Ambitious batch of 0001. Grassy simple hops. Rather weak, even when warm. Pours hazy dirty blond, with thin frothy head. Gently bitter for its stated 52IBU, dry, thin. Possibly single hop, and this is good about this one - more comes to the nose after you taste it. Some spruce. It is thin bodied, but smooth. Medium carbonation, and quite a fast finish. Aftertaste of yeast and some sediment from pellets. Again, looks like Galena to me. Entry homebrew level. To much is asked for it.

33cl. 050 batch (?) Aroma of some weird hops and weird malts and weird cereals. Grassy and indeed smells like a farm in summer - the good kind of smell. Pours clear orange, with superb head, and perfect lacing. Long time ago I saw an IPA like that. Some funky cereal in the taste, and a bit overhopped. Bitter yes, but abv is hidden. Not enough body for the style to my taste. It is nice and medium, but it makes it a bot watery when compared to others. Unfortunately this thinness adds to its drinkability. You just want another one. A splendid beer. Hits all the style marks, and brings in something new and fresh. Extra points: wife approved.

33cl BBE 22.09.16 Pours black with grey-brownish head. Head stays for a while, and blocks all the nice stuff. Once you get to it - aroma is perfectly translated in to taste. It is not always the case, and it is very nicely done here. Clean water. Sweetness feels like it is from honey. Pleasant, well balanced bitterness. A mild yeasty background, slightly sour. This combines nicely with smoked, burnt malts and selected hops. Some sharpness in the finish - feels like a drop of vinegar. Oily-velvety, medium bodied. Some carbonation. A bit powdery, and there is a decent amount of sediment in the bottle also. Alcohol is noticeable during the first sip - start with some light beer befor this one. A solid, well balanced brew.

Fancy 33cl bottle. Makes 1/2 price. Batch 3. BBE 05.06.16 Pours initially clear rose with massive head. 2/3 of the bottle was not able to settle within 3 days. So overal pour is hazier than hefeweizen. Lacing looks like spit. I am sorry. Wild hop clean and citrusy aroma. But it does not translate well in to taste. Powdery, dry, blunt yeasty soapwater, that is heavilly primed with baking soda. Take any lager, throw soda in, and compare what I want to express. But there are some nice flavours hidden beneath all that nasty stuff. If you care to search for it that is. Medium light bodied, powdery and overal feels like I got a last bottle from the botling line with all the unfiltered leftovers. Is that supposed to be like that? Overal feels like a kit ber with some wild hops, brewers gold and galena thrown in as random amount of 3.3g per 33cl. At this stage it is really far away from the price asked.

33cl batch 001. Aroma of rubber, iron, oatmeal, sawdust and ash. Not of smoked stout though. Pours beautiful dark brown with gradient beige head. Looks good. Dry, ashy, burn, overlyroasted, not sweet and not so smoked. Flat carbonation, thin, lightbodied, watery texture. Dry powdery finish, with huge feel of itallian blackest licorice. You can not wash down the aftertaste even if you want to. Not my cup of tea, bt there are fellows who love tha kind of dry, thin, metalic stouts.

33cl. Pours clear licorice black. Nice beige head and nice lacing. Aroma of ash, prunes, licorice. Feels a bit dry and powdery, but not unpleasant. Some sweetness is hidden behind burnt wood and ashes. Somehow I like this combination in this one. Thick, oily, close to full bodied beer. Some carbonation is also there, which is nice. Finish is a bit too dry and rather too long with ginger/licorice/ammonia feel to it. Rum? Maybe there is some, but it does not hit home.

33cl. Feels like it is built on the similar recipe as the original Dark Humor Club. Once you open it - aroma of coconut is quite strong and rather pleasant. Feels like coconut water infused stout. Nice. Add some chocolate, and call it Humorous Bounty Stout. Malty. Well bodied and a pleasant morning desert stout overall. Gentle finish, not dry, not overly sweet.

33cl. Nice coco stout. Pours black with some nice beige head. Head stays, and is a bit too creamy. Medium roasted, not ashed stout is a good choice. Not overly bitter, not to sweet - coco bitterness is very pleasant. Yet it is not too sweet and not do dry. A nice balanced stout. Not quite imperial though.
Tap@Prgu Fresh, fruity, smooth and well bodied. A nice example of style. Pleasant hop combo and a balanced malt palet.

50cl as pictured. Nice bootle, and a good looking beer overal. Pours doppelbock like dark orange, ruby clear colored. Medium head. Aroma of malts yes, tasste - not really. Rather thin, with alcohol in front. Not a competitor to theirs Extra, whichnis much more bock like.

33cl bottle. Fresh citrus and coriander aroma. Wheat and bananas. Some cinamon also. This all goes quite well in tomtaste. Amazing example of how to do Hefeweizen outside Germany. It is refreshing, clean, not obstructed wheat taste. Simple, yet very enjoyable. On of the nicest sourprises from Vormsi.

Tap and bottle in Prgu. Botom of the keg. Both look nice. Bottle is obviously thiner in this comparison. Both pleasant and rye stout like beers. Heavy rye all around. Bready. Not nasty. A good one for rye beer enthusiasts.

50cl can. Slightly better than IPA by A. Le Coq. Thin aroma of water and some wheat. Massive shavingfoam like head - lacing is so unnatural, that it is dificult to wash the glas afterwards. Looks pale blond yes. Thin and tasteless. I am amazed, how it is possible to brew such a thinndrink. You can find some coriander, cloves and wheat, but it is like theirs Weizen but 1/2 diluted. Yeah, it is an alternative to flavourfull beer, as they point it out themselves

50cl can. Cherry aroma indeed. Again, artificial thick shavingcream like head. Thick and massive. Aroma is pleasant. Pours beautiful cherry red. Head is nicely colored. A bit artificial, but looks nice. As far as fruitbeer goes, this is absolutely fine. It is fruity and beery. Not thin, not heavy on alcohol, not too sweet. A balanced summer drink. Much better than other local lowalc variations of fruitbeers and radlers.

50cl can. Once opened, nasty hop fumes feel the room. It is sharp and pungent, as a stale bread. Once poured, aroma is covered by artificially thick and shavingfoam like head. Ipa glass does not help here. Look pale golden, clear and with a massive head. Sour at first, thin hoppy bitterness goes as second. Watery and thin. Surprisingly bad beer for the media compaign going on now. Just a badly brewed lager, and has nothing to do with ale.

33cl 425/1111 Thank you martjoobolut for making it happen. Aroma of sherry/port, smoked barrels, coffee and everything of what original  is. Pours beautifull brownish black. Solid and dense, quite clear and no powdery leftowers floating in the brew. Sweet, malty, with sherry notes well transfered to the beer. Abv is not noticable, and it is not beerlike. More like a desert wine overal. Perfectly balanced brew. I would not change anything in it. I do not want to speculate how much better it would be 5 years from now. It is quite good already. I aged first batch of , and it turned out ok fine, but not so much diffferent. I am to young to describe aged beers.

33cl. Malty with coco and burnt ashy malts. Thinly hoppy. Reminds me of some KARHU Karhu Tosi Vahva, but with a little bit of malt as extra. Most unnatural and out of placed beer I have had in recent years. The style can not be defined as is. Thin yet velvety, caramel and water mixture. Mixed feelings about this one. I was on a hyped bandwagon, so I am kind of disappointed.

FTA: Had this on several occasions in Germany during last years. A review of this Pilsener reminded me to check, if I have ticked it. This a very good, traditional German Pilsener. Freshest I had was a pub in Konstanz. Clear strong taste, nice ABV and it was always a pleasure to enjoy it.
33cl bottle. Malty, gently bitter, not quite a Strong lager, but rather bock beer. Smooth textured. A bit watery, but is closer to medium body. ABV is there, but not unpleasant.

33cl BBE 01.12.2016 HAving BBE printed in the sticker might be a sign of one off beer. Hope it is not the case. Anyho. Pours pitch black, but clear. Thick head at first, but settles nicely with a good lacing. Aroma of schwarz beer and some hops. Not a sweet stout to be hones. Sweet and velvety texture, but rather thin, and leaves not aftertaste. That is finish is also quite short. Mild, thin, watery yet creamy. A simple but very good stout-like black lager. Too much carbonation for a stout. Overall a very good dessert beer - gently bitter, tangy, crispy and sweet. Should be good with the ladies.

50cl can. Pours beautiful orange with frothy head that stays for a long time. Aroma of sweet malt and some mild hops. Medium bodied, thin to the taste, and with a non existent finish. Simple Vienna lager.

33cl x4. Brewed in 2014, bottled 2015. One of the best beers so far for 2016. Malty as hell, bitter, sweet with loads of mixed malt in it. Pours clear dark brown, with decent head. Medium to full bodied. Pleasant smooth textured. It does go well on its own, and with sweet desert also. ABV is not noticeable during drinking, but well noticeable after. Fantastic beer.

33cl. Clear golden with decent head. Aroma of fresh hops as should be. Slightly sour, bitter and not so sweet. Medium bodied, with creamy feel to it. Not tangy, but rather smooth. Carbonation is superb. One of the best Pilseners in a while.
50cl can. Very good for a shandy. Gets you there quicker. No matter the taste sensation.

33cl bottle from Beer Store Vienna. BBE 31.05.2016 Pours hazy pale brown with loads of sediment. Aroma of old yeast and cardboard. Taste is quite unique - sour heller bock, that is yeasty and very strongly acidic. Sharp acidic finish, that is upped by bitterness. Rather thin, heavily carbonated and with a dry mouth feel afterwards. An experiment, where actually you should not experiment. In my opinion this is the style that should be kept as traditional as possible. Watery, acidic (loads of C vitamin and lactobacillus), sour and a challenging brew overall. Get it if you dare.

On tap at OConnors Old Oak Irish Pub@Vienna Poured nicely, with a head that settles. Ruby red, clear. Rather thin bodied. I expected it will remind me of Beamish Red, but it didnt. Barely ok beer, but absolutely not worth the price asked. Nothing to do with Irish, and not really much to do with an ale. Overall a disappointment for the high expectations. Top 10 Irish beers my "you know hwat".

55cl BBE Jan.16. Aroma of caramel malts and gentle hops. Pours Pale orange with thin head. I expected more color for the style. Dry medium bitter with malt background. Some sweet sugars, and not enough bitterness. rough textured, which is also new for the style for me. Dry long finish. Pleasant brew, but try to get yours as fresh as possible and as cold as recomended. Some metallic aftertaste in mine.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: 50cl Fresh in Vienna. Pours hazy dark brown with thin brownish head. Aroma of malt, raisins and sweet licorice indeed. Very close to dunkel, but is weizen and indeed super malty as a good bock should be. Tangy and fizzy, with medium body and a creamy finish. A bit dry. No 8.2% is noticeable at all. One bottle is more than enough for a person. A close sibling of Aventinus Eisbock but rather more gentler. A superb brew!

35.5cl Pours clear orange, with thin head, that goes immediately. Fain aroma of caramel and some malts. Slightly sweet, medium bitter, with some clear caramel and candy sugars. Reminds a bit of faro with extra ABV. Medium bodied, smooth with some sharp alcohol bites. Not fizzy in the glass, but livens up in the mouth. A pleasant drink overall.
